                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d580">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 European War 1939/32a: Circular
                    telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-04T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 4, 1939—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In view of the President’s appeal of September 1, 1939, to the belligerents, and
                    potential belligerents, to refrain from bombing other than strictly military
                    objectives, it is desired that you insist upon the privilege of using your
                    military attaché to inspect promptly by personal visit the scene of any bombing
                    of a nonmilitary objective which may constitute a controversial case of
                    disregard of the humane principle agreed to by the belligerents. It obviously
                    will be necessary to eliminate from your investigations clear-cut cases of
                    attack upon <pb facs="0562" n="550" xml:id="pg_550"/> military objectives
                    incidental to which there may have been loss of civilian life. Prompt factual
                    reports are desired of observed cases of bombing of nonmilitary objectives.</p>
                <p>Same to AmEmbassy, Paris, AmEmbassy, Berlin, and AmEmbassy, Warsaw.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
